&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/jurisdiction/terms/jurisdictional-submission/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/jurisdiction/terms/jurisdictional-submission/> ;
  schema:name "JurisdictionalSubmission" ;
  schema:description "A JurisdictionalSubmission is a triple (G, A, S) — a party G, an authority A with jurisdiction J = (A, T_J, H_J, V), and a subject-matter scope S ⊆ H_J — such that G's act settles V_personal(t, G) = ⊤ for all matters in S, enabling σ^J_t to fix JV(A, φ, t) for φ ∈ S concerning G. The defining structure: submission is the act by which a party fills the personal-jurisdiction gap in V, converting a jurisdiction that has territorial and subject-matter scope but no personal authority over G into one that is complete with respect to G." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/jurisdiction/terms/jurisdictional-submission/> ;
  rdfs:seeAlso "Jurisdiction, JurisdictionalVires, JurisdictionalInvocation, Consent, HohfeldianPosition, Contract, Standing" ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/jurisdiction/terms/jurisdictional-submission/> .

